/* /find-an-accountant/massachusetts/ — t-state-pillar PILLAR. Massachusetts is a CORE state built to the 6-essentials depth
 * (pillar + quickbooks-accountant + small-business-accountant + quickbooks-cleanup + quickbooks-setup +
 * bookkeeping-services); every absent service/industry ROUTES TO GLOBAL. MA is an areaServed-ONLY state: TechBrot serves
 * Massachusetts remotely, so this pillar carries NO street address, NO PostalAddress, NO geo, NO LocalBusiness node, and NO
 * hasMap (all states are areaServed-only (no street address)). Service + areaServed (Commonwealth of Massachusetts + named metros) only;
 * provider = #organization. Mirrors the PA/NJ/MD/VA/OH/MI/GA/NC/AZ/TN/WA/CO core-state exemplars: OMITS `ecosystem`;
 * `industries` cards -> GLOBAL /accounting/industries/*; 5 SERVICE cards = the MA children; `cities` name+county with NO href;
 * pricing rows -> 5 children + global. Massachusetts is the FINAL core state (20th) and finishes Wave D (the Cambridge/Kendall
 * Square biotech and life-sciences hub, Boston finance and healthcare, the university economy).
 *
 * MASSACHUSETTS FACTS (verified 2026-06-26 against the Massachusetts Dept of Revenue and the MA Dept of Family and Medical
 * Leave — see _build/strategy/MA-FACTS.md):
 *  · The 4% "millionaires"/Fair Share surtax — THE MA-distinct hook. Massachusetts taxes most income at a flat 5%, and on top
 *    of that the voter-enacted 4% surtax applies to the portion of taxable income above an inflation-indexed threshold:
 *    $1,083,150 for tax year 2025 and $1,107,750 for tax year 2026 (so 9% total on income above the threshold). The threshold
 *    indexes annually — keep it tied to the tax year. This is the standout MA planning issue: it makes owner compensation,
 *    distributions, business-sale gains, and timing matter enormously near the threshold, and it drives entity/PTE planning.
 *    MA HAS an income tax, so payroll carries Massachusetts state income-tax withholding (Form M-4) — a contrast to WA/TN (no
 *    withholding), like CO.
 *  · The corporate excise — MA's two-measure business tax. A C-corporation pays the greater of two measures combined: an 8%
 *    net-income measure PLUS a property-or-net-worth measure of $2.60 per $1,000, with a $456 minimum excise. (Financial
 *    institutions and S-corps have their own rules.) The CPA computes and files; we keep the books supporting both measures.
 *  · Flat 6.25% sales/use tax — NO local add-on (a clean contrast to CO/WA). The rate is the same everywhere in the state;
 *    use tax mirrors it on untaxed out-of-state purchases. The simplicity here is itself the story for multi-state sellers
 *    used to home-rule or local layering.
 *  · MA Paid Family & Medical Leave (PFML) — the payroll contribution. For 2026 the total contribution is 0.88% of eligible
 *    wages (family + medical leave), split between employer and employee. Employers with fewer than 25 covered individuals are
 *    not required to pay the employer share (an effective 0.46% in that case). Self-employed opt-ins contribute 0.88%. Tied to
 *    2026 — it adjusts.
 *  · The PTE excise (entity-level election) — eligible pass-through entities (S-corps, partnerships) may elect to pay an
 *    entity-level excise at the 5% rate on qualified income, so owners can claim a federal deduction and a refundable MA credit
 *    (a SALT-cap workaround) — especially relevant now that the 4% surtax raises individual exposure. Advisory/coordination
 *    only: the CPA makes the election and files; TechBrot keeps the books PTE-ready.
 *  · Geography — 14 counties (county governments largely abolished, but the counties remain as geographic regions); the economy
 *    is Greater-Boston-centric, with the Cambridge/Route 128/495 innovation belt. Metros: Boston (Suffolk County; finance and
 *    asset management, healthcare, tech), Cambridge (Middlesex County; the global biotech and life-sciences hub — Kendall
 *    Square, MIT, Harvard), Worcester (Worcester County; healthcare, biotech, higher ed), Springfield (Hampden County; the
 *    Pioneer Valley hub), Lowell (Middlesex County; tech and manufacturing), Quincy (Norfolk County; financial services),
 *    Newton (Middlesex County), and Framingham (Middlesex County; the MetroWest corridor).
 *
 * HONESTY: TechBrot is an independent Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor + bookkeeping firm, NOT affiliated with Intuit. It does
 * NOT file MA or federal returns, the income tax (or the 4% surtax), the corporate excise, the sales/use-tax return, the PFML
 * return, or the PTE election as agent; it keeps the books and coordinates with the client's CPA/EA and the Massachusetts Dept
 * of Revenue. Reviews are ONLY the 2 real Clutch reviews (Heidi Schubert, Barbara Best) — no invented reviewers, no
 * AggregateRating. Outcomes/scenarios are explicitly representative composites — never real-client claims. No founder/personal
 * name in visible content; David Westgate appears only as the named lead ProAdvisor/operator. The flat 5% income tax with MA
 * state withholding, the 4% surtax (>$1,083,150 for 2025 / >$1,107,750 for 2026, indexed annually), the corporate excise (8%
 * net-income + $2.60/$1,000 property-or-net-worth, $456 min), the flat 6.25% sales tax (no local), the PFML 0.88% for 2026, and
 * the PTE election are VERIFIED and stated; the surtax threshold is tied to the tax year. */
function stripTags(html){return html.replace(/<[^>]+>/g,"").replace(/&rsquo;/g,"’").replace(/&lsquo;/g,"‘").replace(/&ldquo;/g,"“").replace(/&rdquo;/g,"”").replace(/&mdash;/g,"—").replace(/&ndash;/g,"–").replace(/&rarr;/g,"→").replace(/&amp;/g,"&").replace(/&nbsp;/g," ").replace(/&middot;/g,"·").replace(/&times;/g,"×").replace(/\s+/g," ").trim();}

